      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted RH within ±10% of experimental hemolysis index at validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "Computed RH deviates from experimental hemolysis index by a maximum of 7.2% across the five operating points. Mean absolute error 4.9%. Criterion of ±10% satisfied; see VR04."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Primary QoI (RH) is directly linked to the regulatory acceptance criterion and clinically relevant hemolysis endpoint.",
      "rationale": "RH < 1 is the FDA-accepted acceptance criterion for comparative hemolysis assessment of Class II CPB devices. RH is computed directly from the Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law damage integral applied to tracked Lagrangian parcels. The model narrative notes that this power-law formulation assumes linear superposition of instantaneous damage contributions across fluid parcels, a precondition considered broadly applicable to rotary blood pumps. The QoI is directly traceable to the clinical endpoint of plasma-free hemoglobin elevation. Criterion met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities performed on the same device geometry and fluid conditions as the COU, or with documented justification for any differences.",
      "rationale": "Validation conducted on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry with blood-analog fluid. COU addresses the same device class under CPB conditions. Minor differences in hematocrit (validation: 0%, COU: ~35%) are addressed by scaling viscosity; this scaling relies on the Newtonian fluid assumption, which is stated to be broadly applicable at the shear rates encountered in centrifugal pumps. No specific validation result tests the Newtonian or linearity assumptions at COU-representative hematocrit levels. Overall relevance criterion is considered met at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; solver residual convergence documented.",
      "rationale": "MRL 2 does not require explicit numerical solver error quantification beyond confirming residual convergence. Continuity and momentum residuals converge to <1e-5 for all operating points. Factor scoped to not-assessed per MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not assessed at MRL 2; analyst qualifications documented.",
      "rationale": "MRL 2 does not require formal use-error assessment. Simulation team holds relevant CFD and biofluid mechanics qualifications (CVs on file). Factor not assessed per MRL 2 scope."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Turbulence model and hemolysis damage model selections are justified by literature precedent and sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "SST k-omega turbulence model selected based on published FDA pump benchmark studies demonstrating superior performance for swirling confined flows. Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law hemolysis model selected per regulatory precedent. The model form narrative explicitly states: 'The power-law damage integral assumes that hemolysis contributions from individual fluid parcels are independent and linearly additive — a theoretical precondition considered broadly applicable to centrifugal blood pumps operating in the clinical flow range.' No dedicated validation result is included in this package to verify that the linearity and independence precondition holds under the recirculating, turbulent flow regimes present at the COU operating points (3–6 L/min, 2500–3500 RPM). Sensitivity analysis of model coefficients (alpha, beta exponents) performed; ±15% variation in coefficients produces ±9% change in RH. Model form criterion assessed as met at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "All model inputs (geometry, boundary conditions, fluid properties) are traceable to measurements or published sources with documented uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "Pump geometry from manufacturer CAD files (tolerance ±0.05 mm). Boundary conditions derived from clinical CPB flow specifications. Blood analog viscosity from published rheological data. Inlet turbulence intensity set to 5% based on upstream tubing measurements. All inputs documented in simulation data management system. Criterion met."
    },
